{{Infobox member of the Knesset |image = |birth_date = 1 July 1897 |birth_place = [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]] |Year of Aliyah = 1949 |death_date = {{Death date and age|1981|5|20|1897|7|1|df=yes}} |death_place = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1955|3]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1959|4]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1961|5]] |party1 = [[Herut]] |partyyears1 = 1955-1965 |party2 = [[Gahal]] |partyyears2 = 1965 |minister1 = |}}
'''Binyamin Arditi''' ({{lang-he|בנימין ארדיטי}}, 1 July 1897 &ndash; 20 May 1981) was an [[Israel]]i politician who served as a member of the [[Knesset]] for [[Herut]] and [[Gahal]] between 1955 and 1965.
==Biography== Born in [[Vienna]], Arditi attended high school in [[Sofia]] in [[Bulgaria]]. In 1917 he became a member of the central committee of the [[World Zionist Organization|Zionist Organization of Bulgaria]], on which he remained until 1923. He also chaired the organisation's Sofia branch. In 1925 he established the first Bulgarian [[Revisionist Zionism|Revisionist Zionist]] movement, which he chaired until 1935.
In 1944 he was arrested for Zionist activities, and two years later was arrested again by the [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|communist authorities]] for encouraging [[aliyah|emigration to Palestine]]. Between 1947 and 1949 he served as the Revisionst Zionism representative in the Bulgarian [[Eretz Yisrael Office]].<ref>[http://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mk_eng.asp?mk_individual_id_t=271 Binyamin Arditi: Public Activities] Knesset website</ref>
In 1949 he made [[aliyah]] to Israel, where he became a member of the Herut central committee. In [[Israeli legislative election, 1955|1955]] he was elected to the Knesset on the party's list, and was re-elected in [[Israeli legislative election, 1959|1959]] and [[Israeli legislative election, 1961|1961]], before losing his seat in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1965|1965 elections]].
Arditi also published several books; ''The Role of King Boris in the Expulsion of Bulgarian Jewry'' (1952), ''Bulgarian Jews Under the Nazis'' (1962), ''Bulgarian Jewry – the Sumla Community'' (1968) and ''Famous Bulgarian Jews'' (1971).
He died in 1981 at the age of 83.
