{{Infobox Officeholder | name = Alaowei Broderick Bozimo | nationality = Nigerian | image = | imagesize = 185px | office1 = Federal Minister of Police Affairs | term_start1 = July 2003 | term_end1 = January 2007 | predecessor1 = | successor1 = [[Olu Adeniji]] (Interior) | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1939|1|20|df=y}} | birth_place = | spouse = [[Rosaline Bozimo]] | alma_mater = | occupation = Lawyer | religion= }}
'''Alaowei Broderick Bozimo''' (born 20 January 1939) is a [[Nigeria]]n lawyer who was appointed Minister of Police Affairs by President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] in July 2003. In January 2007 the Ministries of Police Affairs and Internal Affairs were merged into the new Ministry of the Interior, and Bozimo became a Minister of State in the new ministry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.triumphnewspapers.com/archive/DT11012007/obasanjo11107.html |work=Daily Triumph |title=Obasanjo reshuffles cabinet...Swears-in 6 new ministers |author=KABIRU YUSUF |date=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=2010-02-23}}</ref>
Bozimo was born on 20 January 1939, son of a wealthy [[Ijaw people|Ijaw]] businessman, Chief Jonah Oyandongha Bozimo. His father was the first secretary of Western Ijaw division and later the president of the customary court in [[Bomadi]]. Bozimo attended [[Urhobo College]] [[Effurun]], Delta State for his secondary education.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-192430910/bozimo-cheats-death-clocks.html |title=Bozimo Cheats Death, Clocks 70. |work=[[This Day (Nigeria)]] |author=Agha Ibiam |date=January 20, 2009 |accessdate=2011-12-31}}</ref> His wife is [[Rosaline Bozimo]], who was his partner in the law firm Broderick Bozimo & Co and later become the chief justice of [[Delta State]].<ref name=deltabio>{{cite web |url = http://truefaceofdelta.gov.ng/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=82&Itemid=27&limitstart=6 |publisher = Delta State Government |title = The Chief Justice |accessdate = 2010-02-23 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
In May 2008 he denied rumors that he had accepted N17m as share of some alleged deal. He stated that the money had been given him as a minister to pay for emergency medical treatment in London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nm.onlinenigeria.com/templates/?a=12218&z=12 |title=N27m drama: My story, by Bozimo |date=May 18, 2008 |author=IKENNA EMEWU |work=Online Nigeria Daily News |accessdate=2010-02-23}}</ref>
