{{Infobox person | name = Madame Adolphe | birth_name = Madame Max Adolphe | birth_date = September 1925 | disappeared_date = February, 1986 (aged 60) | disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1986|02}} | disappeared_place = [[Haiti]] | nationality = [[Haitians|Haitian]] }}
'''Madame Max Adolphe''' (also known as '''{{nowrap|Max Rosalie Auguste}}''' and '''{{nowrap|Rosalie Bosquet}}'''), born in September 1925,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://miningawareness.wordpress.com/2013/08/17/report-by-the-special-inquest-commission-on-the-troubling-death-of-judge-jean-serge-joseph-part-ii-the-facts/|title=Report by the Special Inquest Commission on the Troubling Death of Judge Jean Serge Joseph, Part II, The Facts|last=miningawareness|date=2013-08-17|website=Mining Awareness +|access-date=2017-06-07}}</ref> was the right hand woman of former [[Haiti]]an president [[François Duvalier]], who used the nickname "Papa{{nbsp}}Doc".
==Biography== Adolphe, then known as Rosalie Bosquet, came to the attention of Duvalier during an attempt on his life. While she was a low ranking officer in the [[Tonton Macoute]], her courage impressed the President so much that he promoted her to the position of [[Prison warden|warden]] at {{nowrap|[[Fort Dimanche]]}}. At the prison, Adolphe continued her strong support of the government and was known for her violent interrogations of political prisoners. She was not viewed as a political threat to the President because of her sex.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooke |first=James |date=1986-02-07 |title=Baby Doc follows Papa and Unleashes the Hated Tontons |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/122163121/ |newspaper=The Age |access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref>
Daily killings, torture, and beatings were typical at the prison during her tenure. She developed a "gruesome reputation for herself as she designed inventive sexual tortures" in Fort Dimanche.<ref name="Girard 2008">{{cite book|last=Girard |first=Philippe R. |title=Africa and the Americas: Culture, Politics, and History: A Multidisciplinary Encyclopedia |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vbZzCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA392 |series=Transatlantic Relations Series |volume=1 |date=2008 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara, California |isbn=978-1-85109-446-2 |lccn=2007035154 |oclc=168716701 |pages=392 |chapter=François Duvalier |editor1-last=Juang |editor1-first=Richard M. |editor2-last=Morrissette |editor2-first=Noelle}}</ref> She was later promoted to the Supreme Head of the ''{{lang|fr|Fillettes Laleau}}'', the female branch of the [[Tonton Macoute]]s.<ref name="Chardy 1986">{{cite news |last=Chardy |first=Alfonso |title=Duvalier left 'Madame Max' to wrath of native Haitians |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lbcwAAAAIBAJ&pg=6710,4933788 |access-date=29 October 2015 |date=13 February 1986 |newspaper=Lakeland Ledger |location=Lakeland, Florida |agency=Knight Ridder/Tribune News Service |via=Google News}}</ref> She also collected a monthly rent check from U.S. Special Forces for the use of her compound.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/haitian-lament-killing-me-softly |title=Haitian Lament: Killing Me Softly |work=The Nation |last=Coughlin |first=Dan |date=1999 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019160859/http://www.thenation.com/article/haitian-lament-killing-me-softly/ |archive-date=19 October 2015 |dead-url=no |quote=Madame Max Adolphe, for instance, the sadistic head of the [[Tonton Macoutes]] under [[François Duvalier|'Papa Doc' Duvalier]], collected a monthly rent check from US Special Forces for the use of her compound. As one young militant put it, 'The pot of rice gets cooked in the name of the children, but it's the adults who eat.' |df= }}</ref> She was reported to have supervised the torture of children and elderly, and to have kept video tapes of the horrors. She liked to arm herself with an Uzi machine-gun.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chardy |first=Alfonso |date=1994-09-18 |title=Island in the Grip of voodoo and Violence |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121339330/ |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref>
==Disappearance== When Papa Doc died in 1971, and his son, [[Jean-Claude Duvalier]] succeeded him, he had Adolphe removed from her post as head of Fort Dimanche. By May 1972 she had been appointed mayor of {{nowrap|Port-au-Prince,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amnesty.ca/sites/amnesty/files/haitiduvalierreport11.pdf#page=33 |title='You Cannot Kill the Truth': The Case against Jean-Claude Duvalier |date=2011 |id=AMR&nbsp;36/007/2011 |publisher=Amnesty International |location=London |page=31 |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151028143518/http://amnesty.ca/sites/amnesty/files/haitiduvalierreport11.pdf |archive-date=28 October 2015 |dead-url=no |quote=Max Rosalie Auguste, also known as 'Max Adolphe', for example, commander of the {{bracket|Tonton&nbsp;Macoutes}} militia and Fort Dimanche prison under François Duvalier, was removed from her roles at the end of 1971. However, by May 1972 she had been appointed mayor of {{nowrap|Port-au-Prince}}. |oclc=776890444 |df= }}</ref>}} which brought her attention to the city's sewage disposal.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Dynastic republicanism in Haiti |date=1973 |journal=The Political Quarterly |publisher=Wiley |volume=44 |issue=1 |page=83 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-923X.1973.tb02078.x |issn=0032-3179 |subscription=yes |quote=Peasants stoned the house of Zacharie&nbsp;Delva, and Eloise&nbsp;Maître has returned to his bakery in the Grande&nbsp;Rue, while the formidable Madame Max Adolphe (at one time commandant of [[Fort&nbsp;Dimanche]], where most important political prisoners were incarcerated or eliminated) has transferred her matronly attentions, as Mayor of {{bracket|Port-au-Prince}}, to the problems of urban sewage disposal.}}</ref> Prior to the end of the Duvalier dynasty in 1986, when the Duvaliers fled the capital, she said "{{bracket|i}}t seems Jean-Claude is leaving the country soon. All militia members will be in danger. Much blood will be shed." Vengeful Haitians killed scores, if not hundreds of former militiamen who used to report to Madame Max.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chardy |first=Alfonso |date=1986-02-12 |title=Where has Haiti's Chief 'Bogeyman' Gone? |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/106474794 |newspaper=The Anniston Star|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref> On February 10, 1986 a soldier guarding her vacant house from looters reported that she was being held prisoner in an army barracks next to the national palace.<ref>{{cite news |last=Press |first=Associated |date=1986-02-11 |title=Haiti Leader Vows to Share Wealth|newspaper=Associated Press }}</ref> By February 1986 she left the country,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.philly.com/1986-02-27/news/26090157_1_justice-minister-gerard-gourgue-luc-desir-emmanuel-ambroise |title=Two Former Duvalier Aides Arrested In Haiti |date=27 February 1986 |newspaper=Philadelphia Inquirer |agency=Inquirer Wire Services |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217223121/http://articles.philly.com/1986-02-27/news/26090157_1_justice-minister-gerard-gourgue-luc-desir-emmanuel-ambroise |archive-date=17 February 2015 |dead-url=no |quote=And Madame Max also has left the country, [[Aubelin Jolicoeur]], director of tourism, said yesterday. |df= }}</ref> but her current whereabouts are unknown. Her daughter, [[Magalie Adolphe Racine]], lives in Haiti and serves as Minister of Youth and Sport.
