'''Ngundeng Bong''' (c. 1830–1890) was a prophet of the [[Nuer people]] of [[South Sudan]].<ref>{{Cite book | isbn = 9780195382075 | title = Dictionary of African Biography | last1 = Henry Louis Gates Jr. | author2 = Emmanuel Akyeampong | author3 = Steven J. Niven | year = 2012 | publisher = Oxford University Press Inc. | page = 463  }}</ref> He presented himself as being an earthly representative of [[Deng (Naath deity)|Deng]], the sky god of the [[Nuer religion]].<ref>{{Cite book| author=[[Douglas H. Johnson]] | chapter = The Prophet Ngundeng & The Battle of Pading | isbn = 9780852557174 | title = Revealing Prophets: Prophecy in Eastern African History | editor1-last = Anderson | editor1-first = David | editor2-first= Douglas Hamilton|editor2-last= Johnson | year = 1995 | publisher = James Currey Ltd. | location = London | page =}}</ref> His prophecies of the breakup of [[Sudan]] are still a factor in the politics of modern South Sudan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://martinplaut.wordpress.com/2014/03/06/south-sudan-riek-machar-and-the-prophets-rod/|title=South Sudan: Riek Machar and the prophet’s rod|author= Martin Plaut | date = 6 March 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201405260645.html|title=South Sudan: A Historical Prophet - Ngundeng Bong's Position in South Sudan Current Crisis|author=Elbow Chuol| date=22 May 2014|publisher=AllAfrica.com}}</ref>

