[[Image:Rudolph G Sonneborn.jpg|right|thumb|Rudolf Sonneborn, during a trip to the [[Negev]], 1950.]]
'''Rudolf Goldschmid Sonneborn''' (June 22, 1898 – June 1, 1986) was an [[oil industry|oil executive]],<ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F60A14FB345415738DDDAD0A94DE405B858AF1D3 Mercurial Publisher: Dorothy Schiff Sonneborn, ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 25, 1965. Retrieved March 23, 2007.]</ref> [[businessman]], and onetime President of [[The State of Israel Bond Drive]]<ref>[http://www.topfoto.co.uk/fotoweb/Preview.fwx?position=1&archiveType=ImageFolder&sorting=ModifiedTimeAsc&search=0859133.jpg&fileId=37D47650838CC38D45944787427ED43BAA16554EB127886169738530E44ED174DB5D9909674395AB80EEC1F06AFB008462EFBB03E0BF594CFC6238CEB7EF1EFC4E38A1BC5CE65D37B9A8053103A90A9B5E22DBD2145EA4BC875B8A1D6640E2073828CF97180CC491B76063335266279B Albert Einstein buys the 2000,000th Israel bond]. - Arquive Photo</ref>
In 1919 (aged 20) Rudolf visited [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] from January to August, acting as the 'Secretary to the [[Zionist]] Commission'.  He was investigating the feasibility of creating an independent Jewish [[State of Israel]] on its territory, achieved 29 years later on May 14, 1948. A detailed account of his trip was recorded in 'Letters Home'.<ref>[http://rudolfsonneborn.blogspot.com/ Rudolf Sonneborn Blogspot]</ref>

On July 1, 1945,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Penslar|first1=Derek|title=Rebels Without A Patron State: How Israel Financed The 1948 War,|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|location=Pennsylvania|page=14|edition=1st|url=https://www.academia.edu/21075807/Rebels_Without_a_Patron_State_How_Israel_Financed_the_1948_War}}</ref> [[David Ben-Gurion]] asked a small gathering of American-Jewish activists at Mr. Sonneborn's apartment to send supplies to the Jewish community and its military force, the [[Haganah]]. The group became a secretive, nationwide organization led by Mr. Sonnenborn, Materials for Israel, also known as the Sonneborn Institute.<ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/search/restricted/article?res=F50714FB3A5B0C778CDDAF0894DE484D81 NY Times Obituary]</ref><ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0806134046 Amazon] [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0595092977 Amazon]</ref><ref>[http://strweb1-12.websys.aol.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,890661,00.html Time]</ref> Sonneborn was the fourth husband of ''[[New York Post]]'' owner and publisher [[Dorothy Schiff]], a granddaughter of the American [[financier]] [[Jacob Schiff]].<ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/search/restricted/article?res=F50714FB3A5B0C778CDDAF0894DE484D81 NY Times Obituary]</ref>

